WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.300
 So the last kind of events that we're going to talk about are network events.

00:00:03.300 --> 00:00:08.800
 That is, code that runs as your JavaScript is talking to the network.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:11.100
 So we can do network operations in JavaScript.

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:17.640
 We can do the entire request-response cycle in JavaScript.

00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:22.200
 The problem is that this has to be an asynchronous process

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:25.140
 because we can't pause our code.

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:27.700
 We can't say stop and read from the server

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:30.540
 because otherwise the browser would lock up.

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:34.500
 So we have to kind of use events and we kind of chain these events together.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:40.700
 We have a start the request and then give me an event when the request is restarted.

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:45.140
 And then as the data is being retrieved, when the data is all retrieved,

00:00:45.140 --> 00:00:46.400
 then you process the request.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:52.300
 And so there's a multi-step process and you do one step and then initiate the second step.

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:58.000
 And so that means that we're never in our JavaScript waiting for anything.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:03.200
 We are responding to an event and then triggering another event

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:05.800
 and then responding to an event and triggering another event,

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:10.000
 but never doing anything that waits in our code.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.400
 This particular code is 14-fetch.htm.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:19.100
 Now fetch is a function that's available and its parameter is a URL.

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:22.600
 So I've got this URL called secret.txt.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:25.800
 Now fetch returns what's called a promise.

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:29.600
 A promise is something that hasn't happened yet, but will happen.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:38.500
 And then you say .then and the then code runs when the fetch has started.

00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:43.100
 And so in this case, and I'm using this sort of short syntax

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:47.900
 because this inside the parentheses of the then you see a function

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:51.000
 that takes a single parameter as the variable response.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.200
 That's my choice as a variable name.

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:57.400
 I console.log and then I return response.text.

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:03.400
 Now what that really is saying is now go retrieve that text which will take some time.

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:07.200
 So response.text itself is another promise.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:12.500
 And so the return value of the first then is itself a promise.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.800
 And that's why you see the second then.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:20.000
 Now the second then happens when the response.text has been retrieved.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.800
 And now we're being handed that as a text string.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:27.700
 And then it says let's run code and console.log that text string.

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:31.200
 So fetch starts and returns a promise.

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:37.100
 Then says when that promise completes run this code and then return another promise.

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:43.100
 And then the second then takes is runs after the second after the promise is retrieved.

00:02:43.100 --> 00:02:44.300
 And then we're done.

00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:47.400
 So you see there's three little steps.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:51.900
 And each of those steps is instantaneous or as fast as we can do it and there's no waiting.

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:59.200
 And each time we have to register a function to respond to the request.

00:02:59.200 --> 00:03:03.600
 So JavaScript calls us back, okay.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:07.500
 And so you can kind of see this happen, right.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:09.200
 The fetch starts.

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:14.500
 The first promise resolves and we see what the response is.

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:18.800
 Now if you look carefully, you see that the response is a 200.

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:22.600
 Which means it looks like we're doing well, right.

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:30.100
 And it has a readable stream, but we have not yet used the body, okay.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.700
 So when it says body used equals false.

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:37.000
 That means that we sort of started the request and it looks like it's going to go well.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.400
 And now we're given a chance to see what we're going once this request has started.

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:43.700
 Now by calling response.text.

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:51.400
 That's a method inside this response object that then says, oh, go back, make a new promise.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:54.500
 And that promise will be fulfilled when we've actually retrieved the text.

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:59.800
 So at this moment where it says console log response, the text hasn't been retrieved yet.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:05.300
 And so we're returning a promise to be fulfilled after the text is received.

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:10.500
 Then when that text receiving is finished, which might take, you know, two seconds or something.

00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:12.600
 And it's like, oh, I've got some text.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:19.700
 So I'm going to call you back, resolve that promise and pass the actual retrieved text string back into us.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:27.300
 And so that's the only moment that what the server has given for secret.txt, which the secret of course is 42 is the text.

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:29.800
 That's when we can actually print it out.

00:04:29.800 --> 00:04:34.100
 We can make this a little bit more succinct and then watch it as it happens.

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:37.200
 So this is 15-fetch.

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:41.900
 So we're going to we're going to do something with this text instead of just printing it.

00:04:41.900 --> 00:04:50.700
 And we're going to use kind of the more succinct contraction style of this function code and not put so many console logs in.

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:53.800
 I was putting console logs so you could see the steps that happen.

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:56.100
 So this is a more typical way of doing something.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:05:00.600
 So we're going to fetch secret.txt, which is your on the server.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:07.900
 When that fetch is successfully started, we resolve the first promise and then we say, OK.

00:05:07.900 --> 00:05:12.200
 And the first response arrow response text response is the parameter to the function.

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:21.200
 And response.text is calling the text method in that, which is the return value to this first promise, which is another promise.

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:25.500
 But that'll be it when that promise resolves it resolve to a text string.

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:28.800
 And that's why the second then says take a variable.

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:32.200
 Again, I could call text string X. It's just a variable in a function call.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.300
 It's just a parameter function call.

00:05:34.300 --> 00:05:39.600
 So call me back. Call me this function I'm making text string.

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:48.900
 And then get doc in that code is document get element ID by ID zap, which is that p tag.

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:53.100
 And I said it's inner text to be the text string that I retrieve from the server.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:06:01.700
 And so you can kind of see that we can do things, we can get data from the server, and then we can move it into our document object model.

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:05.900
 And I tried to do this in the simplest and smallest version.

